[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] Kafka was originally developed at LinkedIn, and was subsequently open sourced in early 2011.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] Jay Kreps, Neha Narkhede and Jun Rao helped co-create Kafka.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] Graduation from the Apache Incubator occurred on 23 October 2012.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] Jay Kreps chose to name the software after the author Franz Kafka because it is "a system optimized for writing", and he liked Kafka's work.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] Apache Kafka is a distributed log-based messaging system that guarantees ordering within individual partitions rather than across the entire topic.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] Unlike queue-based systems, Kafka retains messages in a durable, append-only log, allowing multiple consumers to read at different offsets.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] Kafka uses manual offset management, giving consumers control over retries and failure handling.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] If a consumer fails to process a message, it can delay committing the offset, preventing further progress in that partition while other partitions remain unaffected.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] This partition-based design enables fault isolation and parallel processing while allowing ordering to be maintained within partitions, depending on consumer handling.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] In 2025, Apache Kafka introduced "Queues for Kafka", adding share groups as an alternative to consumer groups.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] This feature enables queue-like semantics where consumers can cooperatively process records from the same partitions, with individual message acknowledgment and delivery tracking.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] Unlike traditional consumer groups where partitions are exclusively assigned, share groups allow the number of consumers to exceed partition count, making it ideal for work-queue patterns while maintaining Kafka's durability and scalability benefits.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] This development addresses the common challenge of "over-partitioning" that many Kafka users face.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] Kafka Connect (or Connect API) is a framework to import/export data from/to other systems.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] It was added in the Kafka 0.9.0.0 release and uses the Producer and Consumer API internally.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] The Connect framework itself executes so-called "connectors" that implement the actual logic to read/write data from other systems.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] Kafka Streams (or Streams API) is a stream-processing library written in Java.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] It was added in the Kafka 0.10.0.0 release.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] The library allows for the development of stateful stream-processing applications that are scalable, elastic, and fully fault-tolerant.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] The main API is a stream-processing domain-specific language (DSL) that offers high-level operators like filter, map, grouping, windowing, aggregation, joins, and the notion of tables.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] Additionally, the Processor API can be used to implement custom operators for a more low-level development approach.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] The DSL and Processor API can be mixed, too.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] For stateful stream processing, Kafka Streams uses RocksDB to maintain local operator state.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] Because RocksDB can write to disk, the maintained state can be larger than available main memory.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] For fault-tolerance, all updates to local state stores are also written into a topic in the Kafka cluster.
[src:azure-event-hubs/apache-kafka] This allows recreating state by reading those topics and feed all data into RocksDB.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] These events may be happening across the various layers of an organization as sales leads, orders or customer service calls.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Or, they may be news items, text messages, social media posts, business processes (such as supply chain), traffic reports, weather reports, or other kinds of data.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] An event may also be defined as a "change of state," when a measurement exceeds a predefined threshold of time, temperature, or other value.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Analysts have suggested that CEP will give organizations a new way to analyze patterns in real-time and help the business side communicate better with IT and service departments.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] CEP has since become an enabling technology in many systems that are used to take immediate action in response to incoming streams of events.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Applications are now to be found (2018) in many sectors of business including stock market trading systems, mobile devices, internet operations, fraud detection, the transportation industry, and governmental intelligence gathering.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The vast amount of information available about events is sometimes referred to as the event cloud.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] 2. the appearance of a man in a tuxedo with a woman in a flowing white gown.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] From these events the monitoring system may infer a *complex event*: a wedding.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] CEP as a technique helps discover complex events by analyzing and correlating other events: the bells, the man and woman in wedding attire and the rice flying through the air.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Commercial applications of CEP exist in variety of industries and include the detection of credit-card fraud, business activity monitoring, and security monitoring.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The CEP area has roots in discrete event simulation, the active database area and some programming languages.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The activity in the industry was preceded by a wave of research projects in the 1990s.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] According to the first project that paved the way to a generic CEP language and execution model was the Rapide project in Stanford University, directed by David Luckham.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] In parallel there have been two other research projects: Infospheres in California Institute of Technology, directed by K.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Mani Chandy, and Apama in University of Cambridge directed by John Bates.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The commercial products were dependents of the concepts developed in these and some later research projects.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Community efforts started in a series of event processing symposia organized by the Event Processing Technical Society, and later by the ACM DEBS conference series.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] One of the community efforts was to produce the event processing manifesto.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] CEP is used in operational intelligence (OI) products to provide insight into business operations by running query analysis against live feeds and event data.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] OI collects real-time data and correlates against historical data to provide insight and analysis.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Multiple sources of data can be combined to provide a common operating picture that uses current information.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] In network management, systems management, application management and service management, people usually refer instead to event correlation.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] As CEP engines, event correlation engines (*event correlators*) analyze a mass of events, pinpoint the most significant ones, and trigger actions.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] However, most of them do not produce new inferred events.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Instead, they relate high-level events with low-level events.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Inference engines, e.g., rule-based reasoning engines, typically produce inferred information in artificial intelligence.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] However, they do not usually produce new information in the form of complex (i.e., inferred) events.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] A more systemic example of CEP involves a car, some sensors and various events and reactions.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Imagine that a car has several sensors—one that measures tire pressure, one that measures speed, and one that detects if someone sits on a seat or leaves a seat.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] In the first situation, the car is moving and the pressure of one of the tires moves from 45 psi to 41 psi over 15 minutes.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] As the pressure in the tire is decreasing, a series of events containing the tire pressure is generated.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] In addition, a series of events containing the speed of the car is generated.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The car's Event Processor may detect a situation whereby a loss of tire pressure over a relatively long period of time results in the creation of the "lossOfTirePressure" event.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] This new event may trigger a reaction process to note the pressure loss into the car's maintenance log, and alert the driver via the car's portal that the tire pressure has reduced.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] In the second situation, the car is moving and the pressure of one of the tires drops from 45 psi to 20 psi in 5 seconds.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] A different situation is detected—perhaps because the loss of pressure occurred over a shorter period of time, or perhaps because the difference in values between each event were larger than a predefined limit.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The different situation results in a new event "blowOutTire" being generated.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] This new event triggers a different reaction process to immediately alert the driver and to initiate onboard computer routines to assist the driver in bringing the car to a stop without losing control through skidding.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] In addition, events that represent detected situations can also be combined with other events in order to detect more complex situations.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] For example, in the final situation the car is moving normally and suffers a blown tire which results in the car leaving the road and striking a tree, and the driver is thrown from the car.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] A series of different situations are rapidly detected.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The combination of "blowOutTire", "zeroSpeed" and "driverLeftSeat" within a very short period of time results in a new situation being detected: "occupantThrownAccident".
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Even though there is no direct measurement that can determine conclusively that the driver was thrown, or that there was an accident, the combination of events allows the situation to be detected and a new event to be created to signify the detected situation.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] This is the essence of a complex (or composite) event.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] It is complex because one cannot directly detect the situation; one has to infer or deduce that the situation has occurred from a combination of other events.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] A natural fit for CEP has been with business process management (BPM).
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] BPM focuses on end-to-end business processes, in order to continuously optimize and align for its operational environment.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] However, the optimization of a business does not rely solely upon its individual, end-to-end processes.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Seemingly disparate processes can affect each other significantly.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Consider this scenario: In the aerospace industry, it is good practice to monitor breakdowns of vehicles to look for trends (determine potential weaknesses in manufacturing processes, material, etc.).
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Another separate process monitors current operational vehicles' life cycles and decommissions them when appropriate.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The integration of CEP and BPM must exist at two levels, both at the business awareness level (users must understand the potential holistic benefits of their individual processes) and also at the technological level (there needs to be a method by which CEP can interact with BPM implementation).
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] For a recent state of the art review on the integration of CEP with BPM, which is frequently labeled as Event-Driven Business Process Management, refer to.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Computation-oriented CEP's role can arguably be seen to overlap with Business Rule technology.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] For example, customer service centers are using CEP for click-stream analysis and customer experience management.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] CEP software can factor real-time information about millions of events (clicks or other interactions) per second into business intelligence and other decision-support applications.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] These "recommendation applications" help agents provide personalized service based on each customer's experience.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The CEP application may collect data about what customers on the phone are currently doing, or how they have recently interacted with the company in other various channels, including in-branch, or on the Web via self-service features, instant messaging and email.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The application then analyzes the total customer experience and recommends scripts or next steps that guide the agent on the phone, and hopefully keep the customer happy.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] A time series database is a software system that is optimized for the handling of data organized by time.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Time series are finite or infinite sequences of data items, where each item has an associated timestamp and the sequence of timestamps is non-decreasing.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Elements of a time series are often called ticks.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The timestamps are not required to be ascending (merely non-decreasing) because in practice the time resolution of some systems such as financial data sources can be quite low (milliseconds, microseconds or even nanoseconds), so consecutive events may carry equal timestamps.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Time series data provides a historical context to the analysis typically associated with complex event processing.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] This can apply to any vertical industry such as finance and cooperatively with other technologies such as BPM.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The ideal case for CEP analysis is to view historical time series and real-time streaming data as a single time continuum.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] What happened yesterday, last week or last month is simply an extension of what is occurring today and what may occur in the future.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] An example may involve comparing current market volumes to historic volumes, prices and volatility for trade execution logic.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Or the need to act upon live market prices may involve comparisons to benchmarks that include sector and index movements, whose intra-day and historic trends gauge volatility and smooth outliers.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Complex event processing is a key enabler in Internet of things (IoT) settings and smart cyber-physical systems (CPS) as well.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Processing dense and heterogeneous streams from various sensors and matching patterns against those streams is a typical task in such cases.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] The majority of these techniques rely on the fact that representing the IoT system's state and its changes is more efficient in the form of a data stream, instead of having a static, materialized model.
[src:azure-event-hubs/complex-event-processing] Reasoning over such stream-based models fundamentally differs from traditional reasoning techniques and typically require the combination of model transformations and CEP.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:azure-event-hubs/data-pipeline] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:azure-event-hubs/event-stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
