[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:azure-event-hubs/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] It is usually used in the context of big data in which it is generated by many different sources at high speed.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Data streaming can also be explained as a technology used to deliver content to devices over the internet, and it allows users to access the content immediately, rather than having to wait for it to be downloaded.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Big data is forcing many organizations to focus on storage costs, which brings interest to data lakes and data streams.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Before explaining the benefits of streaming data, it is important to understand the difference between digitization and digitalization.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Digitiztion is the creation (encoding) of digital information (e.g., a file) using analog information.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] When a digital camera takes a photo, the light entering its lens is the analog information, and the photo file is the digital representation of said light.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] The camera is digitizing the visual information.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Digitalization describes mainly a socio-technical process, where a society or organization adopts digital forms for data storage.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Converting analog information in a library (physical books) into digital formats (eBook documents), for example, would be digitalization of said library.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Within the context of data streaming, media has been digitized since the early 1990s with the adaptation of digital recordings, e.g., storing music and videos in digital forms, while the digitalization of media did not start until the beginning of the 21st century.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] The digital innovation management like Metabott theories mention five characteristics of streaming data: homogenization and decoupling, modularity, connectivity, digital traces and programmability.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Homogenization and decoupling. “Because all digital information assumes the same form, it can, at least in principle, be processed by the same technologies.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Consequently, digitizing has the potential to remove the tight couplings between information types and their storage, transmission, and processing technologies”.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Within the context of data streaming, this means in theory that one can stream data now from any digital device.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] It also reduces the demand and use of music and films on CDs for example.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] One of the consequences of homogenization & decoupling is the decline of marginal costs.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] The marginal cost of data streaming is because it solely uses digital information, which can be transmitted, stored, and computed in fast and low-cost ways.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] An example of an industry that has low marginal costs due to data streaming is the music industry.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Producers can now digitize songs and upload them on Spotify, instead of paying for the creation of the physical albums and distributing them.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Another consequence is convergent user experience, meaning that previously separated experiences are now brought together in one product.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Data streaming is also modular, because systems components may be separated and recombined mainly for flexibility and variety.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Data streaming works in different application versions and systems such as iOS.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] It is also possible to change the speed of data streaming.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] A consequence of modularity is the creation of platforms.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Data streaming platforms bring together analysis of information, but more importantly, they are able to integrate data between different sources (Myers, 2016).
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] IBM streams for example is an analytics platform that enables the applications developed by users to gather, analyze and correlate information that comes to them from a variety of sources (IBM).
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] The third characteristic, connectivity, describes that a digital technology not only connects applications, devices and users but also connects customers and firms.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Streaming services for example connects a vast collection of music and films of ‘producers’ with their consumers, so how music on Spotify can easily reach a vast group of consumers.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Another example would be data of transport vehicles that can also be connected to firms with streaming applications, via vehicle-to-roadside communications.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] UPS does this for example to ‘calculate’ the optimal delivery routes by streaming real time big data and thereby reducing time to deliver packages.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Interoperability, which is the ability of a product or system to work with other products or systems, is a consequence of connectivity.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] For instance, the music industry is interoperable, because some music platforms have integrated social media platforms.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Another of connectivity is network externality.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] This means that the value of a good to a user increases with the number of other users (installed base) of the same or similar good.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Data streaming technology can utilize network externalities, because it brings together supply and demand of large networks of creators and consumers.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] This is very much the case at popcorn time, a service where people can stream latest movies on demand.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] These streams work better when people have used their content.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] The latter has to do with the fact that if one streams content he/she automatically also down/uploads content.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] While a streaming service is being used it leaves Digital Traces, which simply describes the fact that all digital technologies leave a digital trace from the user.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] In the past, when media was sold, the seller/provider only had information about the transaction itself.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] With data streaming it has become possible to actually track the behaviour of the users because it occurs in real time, directly from the distributor/providers.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Morris and Powers describe this as opening the 'black box' of consumption.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Providers of streaming services, for example, are now able to track detailed consuming behavior of the user, which in turn, they use to influence the user's decision-making process by creating algorithms to further develop a service.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] This kind of streaming has changed the way people consume media, which in time offered new possibilities for new ideas.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] These are also referred to as wakes of innovation and occur in places one would not initially expect.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] For instance, data streaming has enabled the development of sensors, for example that are used in a lot of sectors for different purposes.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] In the manufacturing sector data streaming is used for real-time analysis to improve operations.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] In healthcare sector sensors are being used for connected medical devices to create hubs of patients and healthcare providers, that can trigger alerts when a patient has a medical emergency.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Finally, programmability, a characteristic that describes that an innovative digital technology can be reprogrammed, improved and/or updated.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Consequences of programmability are emerging functionalities.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] The most applicable functionality is incompleteness, which means that products and services are never finished, which is the case for data streaming because suppliers will keep refreshing their models .
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] However, a more influential consequence of the programmability, and also of connectivity is the servitization of digital media content.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Data streaming has caused a shift towards pay for use instead of pay for ownership;.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] This is happening in the video and music streaming industry, think of Netflix or Spotify.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] You have to pay to use the service, instead of owning a product.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] This was the case with buying an album or DVD, whereas now it is possible to access thousands of songs or movies.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Data streaming is becoming more useful and necessary in today's world and is being applied in a broad range of industries, some of which that have been already mentioned in examples such as the medical or transportation industry.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Besides these examples, there are probably many more applications for data streaming.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] However, data streaming has had the biggest implications for the audio, video and telecom industry because of the creation of streaming services.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Streaming services have majorly influenced how people consume their media nowadays.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Since the streaming services have had the most significant impact using the data streaming technology, this will be the main focus further on this page.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] The process of technological convergence, which appears because different industries increasingly rely on the same set of technological skills in their production processes, leads to closer relations between markets that was previously not highly related.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] For example, social media platforms such as Facebook and Twitter are providing live-streaming services, which allows global news publishers to connect directly with the right audiences as well as a far wider range of audiences than they otherwise would have reached.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] This has led to a change in which how and where news publishers are interacting with their audiences, and how they use social media services to deliver their service.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] An industry that is impacted by data streaming is the Video Streaming industry.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Consumers are now demanding videos to be available at immediate request, meaning that it is no longer only the quality resolution of image that acts as important performance metrics in the media industry, but also how quickly video starts to play.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] The video industry underwent some of the same changes as the music industry.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] The video industry gained revenue by selling DVDs to customers and selling rights to cinemas and television channels.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] In 1997, the first online distributors began, but this was still small over a decade later mainly due to lower quality compared to hardcopy films.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] The third wave of streaming services such as Netflix, iTunes, Hulu, Amazon and Blockbuster have changed the film market.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] The digitization, digitalization and underlying technologies of streaming have created these streaming services which essentially caused this disruption.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] With the rise of streaming firms in the film industry, the sales of physical DVDs vanished completely.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] An important difference between the music and film industry is that within the film industry, streaming services such as iTunes and Netflix are ‘destroying’ revenue (Sullivan, 2009).
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Because of this less films are produced and consequently there are less jobs in this industry.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] On contrary, cinemas are still important in the film industry, but the share of movies and series that are streamed by customers is rising very fast.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] It replaced the DVD, changed the performance metrics of the incumbents and can thus be seen as disruptive.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Another impacted industry is the Music Streaming industry.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] In 2017, streaming accounted for 43% of revenues in the music industry, and this was the third year of consecutive growth.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] New music streaming services such as Spotify and Apple Music challenges the traditional label companies, which are now risking to be outcompeted by new business models.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Before the rapid adaption of streaming, in 2000 the music industry was experiencing what turned out to be a 15-year-long continued stagnation in revenue, which was due to the high CD prices needed to cover the costs of record labels.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] In 2015, the streaming technology overtook the market by allowing revenues to increase by saving costs on labels, and artists to have a more steady income by making money on streams, rather than being reliant on a full album or CD to do well after being published.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Furthermore, data streaming also has an impact on the Game Streaming industry.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Game streaming is caused by the considerable growth of cloud computing, which allow gamers to access a greater variety of games without having to own expensive hardware.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Cloud computing operates as an enabler to the development of game streaming, where hardware and content is accessed from the cloud, leading to a change in offering greater flexibility in content distribution.
[src:azure-event-hubs/streaming-data] Game streaming allowed by cloud technology will drive changes in the gaming industry, where it is the hardware configuration of machines in the cloud that will be the developers, cost and time will be reduced to develop a greater ability of user reach around the world.
